826957703, "span": {"begin": 1525, "end": 1536}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:885"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CCK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9967131614685059, "span": {"begin": 1659, "end": 1662}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:886"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CCK1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9962275624275208, "span": {"begin": 1674, "end": 1688}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "vagal afferent nerve fibers", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7009487748146057, "span": {"begin": 1706, "end": 1733}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000109"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "acetylcholine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981416463851929, "span": {"begin": 1779, "end": 1792}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1131"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "M3 muscarinic cholinergic receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9887173771858215, "span": {"begin": 1811, "end": 1846}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9925379157066345, "span": {"begin": 2147, "end": 2153}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:886"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CCK receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.996691107749939, "span": {"begin": 2170, "end": 2183}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "acinar cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.599258542060852, "span": {"begin": 2197, "end": 2209}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:887"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CCK2 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955778121948242, "span": {"begin": 2249, "end": 2263}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "acinar cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8281210064888, "span": {"begin": 2318, "end": 2330}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:885"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CCK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952827095985413, "span": {"begin": 2334, "end": 2337}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9896317720413208, "span": {"begin": 2416, "end": 2422}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:886"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CCK1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9900879859924316, "span": {"begin": 2479, "end": 2493}}], "text": "The major function of pancreatic exocrine secretion is secretion of digestive enzymes, fluid, and bicarbonate in response to food intake. Zymogen granules located at the apical site of pancreatic acinar cells contain the precursors of multiple digestive enzymes, such as trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, proesterase, procarboxypeptidase A and B, as well as pancreatic lipase and amylase &alpha;. These precursors are secreted into the small intestine, where trypsinogen is converted to trypsin by enteropeptidase, and the newly generated trypsin activates more trypsinogen molecules and other proenzymes [Berg JM et al, 2002].  Pancreatic exocrine secretion is regulated mainly by CCK released from CCK-producing I cells located within the mucosa of the small intestine. CCK stimulates exocrine secretion either directly via CCK receptors expressed on acinar cells or indirectly by the vagovagal reflex via CCK receptors. There are species differences in these CCK regulatory mechanisms [Singer MV and Niebergall-Roth E, 2009; Chandra R and Liddle RA, 2009].  There are two types of CCK receptors: CCK1 (CCK-A) and CCK2 (CCK-B or gastrin) receptors. The CCK1 receptor exhibits high affinity to all CCK isoforms, whereas the CCK2 receptor exhibits affinity to both CCK and gastrin, in which the last five amino acid sequences at the C-terminus end are identical [Dufresne M et al, 2006; Rehfeld JF, 2017].  In rats, pancreatic acinar cells express mainly CCK1 receptors, and blood CCK directly stimulates exocrine secretion and acinar cell proliferation [Dufresne M et al, 2006]. Moreover, the vagal afferent nerves also stimulate pancreatic exocrine secretion; CCK stimulates CCK1 receptors expressed on the vagal afferent nerve fibers of the vago&ndash;vagal reflex loop, and the acetylcholine generated acts on M3 muscarinic cholinergic receptors to promote pancreatic exocrine secretion [Bourassa J et al, 1999; Adler G, 1997; Ji B et al, 2001; Li Y et al, 1997; Owyang C, 1996]. Moreover, when the gastric wall is distended with ingested food, the vagus nerve is stimulated to promote pancreatic exocrine secretion [Dufresne M et al, 2006].  In humans, the density of CCK receptors expressed on acinar cells is lower than that in rodents, whereas CCK2 receptors are dominantly expressed. Therefore, the responses of acinar cells to CCK seem to be weaker compared with rodents, and pancreatic exocrine secretion in humans is regulated mainly by vagal afferent nerves expressing CCK1 receptors [Wang BJ and Cui ZJ, 2007; Owyang C, 1996; Pandiri AR, 2014].", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:46:58 +0000 2026"}